:[{"name":"Bulkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Bulkeley, from Old English <i>bulluc</i> ‘bullock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: Peter Bulkeley (1583–1659), Puritan divine, who came from Bedfordshire, England, was a founder of Concord, MA, in 1636."],"variants":[{"name":"Bulkley","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Bulkeley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bulkeley was born about 1346, in Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, his father, Richard Bulkeley of Cheadle, was 36 and his mother, Agnes de Cheadle, was 38. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Bostock. He died in 1379, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1346–1379":"umbes 1346–1379","1345–1362":"1345–1362","1346–1379":"1346–1379","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1350–1385":"1350–1385","1369–1391":"1369–1391","1374–1474":"1374–1474","1312–1350":"1312–1350","1310–1347":"1310–1347","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","22 Feb 1369":"22. veebruar 1369","1347":"1347","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1346":"1346","about 1327":"umbes